<h1>About</h1>

<h2>What about Amble?</h2>
<p>
  Inspired by the incredibly functional user interface of Urbanspoon,
  we wanted to create a mobile application to help tourists 
  discover interesting new places in Melbourne quickly and easily.
  
  The concept: a visitor will wander around, discovering sights and activities,
  while Amble will provide a steady stream of imagery of further locations to explore.
  
  The core idea is that the application is a stream of easily digestible information,
  whilst providing only those features which are absolutely necessary.
</p>

<blockquote>
  In short: to help new people discover new places&hellips; 
    to be as helpful as possible whilst distracting as little as possible.
</blockquote>

<h3>Goals</h3>
<p>
  The main goal of Amble was, as with all great mobile applications, 
  to get the data to the user as quickly as possible. Further, we focussed 
  on the following:
  
  <ul>
    <li>
      <em>Clear, graphical Places.</em>
      <p>Mobile users don't have time to read long descriptions. A picture tells
        a thousand words.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <em>Simple Sign-on.</em>
      <p>We chose to use Facebook Connect to make log in as simple as possible 
           for the vast majority of users.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <em>Simple Interface.</em>
      <p>
        We pared the features down to the absolute minimum required, in order to
        build a great product.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <em>Great Data.</em>
      <p>
        We used the wealth of data provided by the Victorian Government, and
        cross-referenced it with other online sources to create a very high-quality
        dataset.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>

<blockquote>
  Our goals: to craft a more human approach to discovery&hellips; 
  to encourage activity and meaningful connections.
</blockquote>

<p>
